# Project: [Project Name]
# Phase: [MVP / v1.0 / Production]

## Before EVERY Task

Read these files first:
1. `ARCHITECTURE.md` — system design and schema
2. `README.md` — project scope and current phase
3. `LEARNINGS.md` — known gotchas and solutions
4. Current sprint plan in `dev-docs/sprints/`

## Iron-Clad Developer Rules

### Quality Standards
- **Unit tests are mandatory** — write tests for every piece of business logic, every utility function, every API endpoint. No exceptions.
- **Smoke test after every change** — after any development, debugging, or fix, run the app and verify it works end-to-end. No stone unturned.
- **Browser/UI testing required** — for any frontend change, verify visually in the browser. Describe what should appear and confirm it does.
- **Handle errors explicitly** — no silent failures, no empty catch blocks. Log meaningful messages. Return proper error responses.
- **Comment the "why"** — every non-obvious decision gets a comment explaining WHY, not what. Aim for heavy commenting on business logic.
- **Every function gets a docstring** — parameters, return type, purpose. No exceptions for public functions.

### Development Workflow
- **Plan mode FIRST** — always propose an approach and get approval before writing code
- **One task at a time** — do not start working on side issues discovered during a task. Document them for later.
- **Commit working code** — never commit broken code. If tests fail, fix them before committing.
- **Update docs after every task** — LEARNINGS.md for gotchas, sprint plan for status, ARCHITECTURE.md if structure changed.
- **Ask questions when anything is unclear** — if a task spec is ambiguous, a requirement contradicts the architecture, or you're unsure about the user's intent, ask before building. A 30-second question beats 30 minutes of rework.
- **Never start serious development without a task document** — diagnosing and fixing 2-3 small bugs in plan mode is acceptable, but any substantial work must have a task doc first. Even bug fixes should be documented in LEARNINGS.md or as an annex to the relevant task doc, recording what the bug was and what the fix was. This makes the dev-docs folder large on complex projects, but it's worth it as a map of how the project was built for any future AI work on the codebase.
- **Handle API timeout errors gracefully** — if you receive timeout errors when writing to a file, break the task into smaller chunks. For example, write the CSS head first, then the body HTML in sections, then the footer. Don't keep retrying the same large write.

### Architecture Rules
- **Follow existing patterns** — check how similar things are done in the codebase before creating new patterns
- **No new dependencies without discussion** — justify any new package and get approval
- **Use absolute imports** — use `$lib/`, `@/`, or project aliases. No relative imports crossing module boundaries.
- **Database changes need migrations** — never modify the database schema without a proper migration file

### Control Panel Conventions (if project has a backend)

**Deployment monitoring:**
- Maintain `deployment.json` at project root listing all services, health endpoints, and deploy methods
- Update it whenever a service is added, removed, or its URL changes
- Implement `/api/health` returning `{ status: 'ok', timestamp: '...' }`

**Data visibility:**
- When creating enum-like data or option sets, create a JSON file in `static-data/` first
- The control panel reads these files — check there before inventing dropdown values in code

**Automation flows:**
- Every backend automation (webhook, cron, pipeline) MUST have:
  1. A `@flow` JSDoc annotation declaring name, trigger, and steps
  2. An entry in the flow registry file
  3. `flowLog()` calls at each logical step with sanitised input/output
- `flowLog()` MUST NEVER include passwords, tokens, API keys, or raw JWTs
- `flowLog()` MUST NEVER crash the actual flow — always wrap in try/catch

**User journey testing:**
- After implementing any user-facing feature, append a test journey to `USER_JOURNEYS.json`
- Include: journey name, user role, exact steps, exact expected outcomes
- The control panel renders these as interactive pass/fail checklists

**Security checks:**
- When referencing env var names in monitoring/check code, ALWAYS read `.env.example` first — never invent names from conventions
- All admin routes must have auth guards
- All API routes (except public webhooks) must verify authentication
- Error responses must not leak stack traces

### Frontend Tweaker Conventions (all projects with a UI)

**Text management (i18n):**
- ALL user-facing text MUST use i18n translation keys — no hardcoded strings in components
- Use i18next (or framework equivalent: svelte-i18n, vue-i18n, next-intl)
- Set up i18n in Sprint 1 during project scaffolding, even for monolingual apps
- Keys MUST be hierarchical by page/feature: `dashboard.header.title`, `auth.login.submit_button`
- Never use generic keys like `text1`, `label2`, `btn_a`
- Interpolated variables use double braces: `"greeting": "Welcome back, {{name}}"`
- Pluralisation uses i18next suffix convention: `_one`, `_other`, `_zero`
- Locale files live in `src/locales/` (or framework convention path)

**Style tokens (@tweak annotations):**
- All tweakable visual properties MUST use CSS custom properties
- Every custom property that a user might want to adjust MUST have a `@tweak` annotation comment
- Annotation format: `/* @tweak [Label] | [type: color|range] | [optional: state, breakpoint] */`
- Properties requiring annotations: font sizes, colours, spacing (padding/margin), border radii, shadows, opacity, transition durations, hover/focus/disabled state values
- Group tokens hierarchically in a `design-tokens.css` or at the top of component files:
  - Brand tokens: `--brand-primary`, `--brand-dark`, `--brand-accent`
  - Semantic tokens: `--text-primary`, `--bg-surface`, `--border-default`
  - Component tokens: `--card-padding`, `--btn-font-size`, `--hero-title-color`
- Dark mode: define overrides in `.dark {}` with matching `@tweak` annotations suffixed "(dark mode)"
- Components MUST reference variables, never raw values, for any property that's annotated

**Link management:**
- All external URLs and internal navigation hrefs MUST reference `links.json`
- No hardcoded URLs in components — import from the config file
- Structure: group by purpose (`social`, `cta`, `footer`, `legal`)
- Update `links.json` when adding or changing any link destination

**SEO and meta content:**
- All page titles, meta descriptions, and OG image paths MUST reference `meta.json`
- No hardcoded `<title>` or `<meta>` tags in page components
- Structure: one key per page/route with `title`, `description`, and optional `og_image`
- Meta descriptions should target 150-160 characters

**Convention file maintenance:**
- When adding a new page: update `meta.json`, add i18n keys for all text, add links to `links.json`
- When adding a new component: add `@tweak` annotations for all visual properties, add i18n keys for all text
- When modifying an existing component: ensure all four convention layers are updated in the same task
- NEVER leave orphaned keys in convention files after removing a component

### What NOT To Do
- Do NOT skip tests to save time
- Do NOT refactor code outside the current task scope
- Do NOT add features not in the current task specification
- Do NOT use `any` types (TypeScript) or skip type safety
- Do NOT store secrets or credentials in code
- Do NOT ignore linter warnings
- Do NOT install dependencies without first searching the web for the latest stable version — training data may be months out of date
- Do NOT overwrite production `.env` files with local values — always confirm the target environment before any deployment action
- Do NOT push code to the production stack directly — push to dev, test, then the user manually promotes to production
- Do NOT estimate how long tasks will take — AI time predictions are wildly inaccurate and misleading. A task that takes 30 minutes of focused AI-assisted work gets estimated at "2-3 days." Omit all time estimates from plans, task docs, and status updates.

### Git & Security Hygiene
- **Set up `.gitignore` from the start** and review it regularly — no API keys, SSH keys, `.env` files, or credentials should ever reach the repository
- When adding new environment variables, always update `.env.example` with the variable name and a description (not the actual secret value)
- Before any git push, verify that `.gitignore` is covering all sensitive files

## Confidence Scoring

After each task, provide:

```
## Confidence: X/10

**Met:**
- [x] [Criterion]
- [x] [Criterion]

**Deferred:**
- [ ] [Thing] → [Which phase/sprint]

**Tests:**
- Unit: [X/Y passing]
- Smoke: [Verified / Not verified]
```

**8/10 minimum to proceed.** Below 8 means fix it before moving on.

## Ask Human When

- Security-related decisions
- Architectural changes not in the spec
- Ambiguous requirements
- Anything destructive (deleting data, dropping tables)
- Confidence below 8
- Task is taking significantly longer than estimated
- A discovered issue affects another part of the app (write a task doc instead of fixing it inline)

## Tech-Specific Rules

### SvelteKit (if applicable)
- After ANY code change, run `npm run build` and check for build errors before declaring the task complete
- If build artifacts seem stale (changes not appearing), run `rm -rf .svelte-kit && npm run build` for a clean rebuild
- When modifying shared utilities, layouts (`+layout.svelte`, `+layout.server.ts`), or server load functions, test ALL pages that could be affected — not just the page you were working on. Layout changes propagate to every child route.
- Guard all browser-only APIs (`window`, `document`, `localStorage`) with `if (browser)` from `$app/environment` — unguarded access causes 500 errors on the server-side render
- If a page throws a 500 error, check the **server terminal output** — the actual error is there, not in the browser. The browser only shows a generic "Internal Error" message.
- Use `+error.svelte` boundary pages to catch and display rendering errors gracefully

### Drizzle ORM + PostgreSQL (if applicable)
- After any schema migration on the dev server, ALWAYS run the seed script — the frontend will show stale data if only the schema is updated without re-seeding
- Include the seed command in the deployment checklist: migrations first, then seed, then verify
- When deploying to the cloud dev server, always confirm both schema and data are current before testing
- Use upsert logic in seed scripts (insert or update) rather than truncate-and-reinsert, to avoid data loss on production

